        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>To produce the simulated ALMA observation of XMMU J2235.3--2257 we have used the beta-model fit for the gas density from Rosati et al. (2009), and the temperature profile from a similar mass cool-core cluster WARP J1415.1+3612 at z=1.03 from Santos et al. (2012). The input cluster map has a central Comptonization value of y_0 = 1.6E-4, corresponding to a flux  density of roughly 55 uJy/beam for the synthesized beam size of 3" in a compact configuration. Suggested array configuration is C32-2, at a frequency near 100 GHz (band 3) with the full 7.5 GHz bandwidth. In approximately 2 hour on-source integration the noise achievable is 10 uJy/beam, sufficient for a better than 5-sigma detection of the SZ signal in the core region. The S/N can be further improved by smoothing the image, as the 3" resolution corresponds to only 25 kpc at the cluster redshift, and the core region is roughly 100 kpc across. Total time request for the main array including overheads is 4 hours.

Due to the large angular extent of the SZ signal, even for z &gt; 1 clusters, there will be significant flux loss for a lack of short baselines in the main array (Fig.4 left), so additional observation from the compact array is requested. We expect the source size to be roughly 40", although the beta-model unrealistically suggests some flux at larger scales. The lack of total power antennas in the current cycle is not a problem because we have access to a wide-angle bolometric image of this cluster (discussed below).

The ALMA time estimator recommends a multiplication factor ~ 2 for the Compact Array, giving an on-target ACA observing time 4 hours. The rms noise is 75 uJy per synthesized beam of 20" with the ACA. However, we shall be able to improve the S/N significantly for azimuthally averaged radial profile analysis (Fig.4 right), expecting to get better than 6-sigma constraints on the large-scale emission. We remark that this ACA measurement will already be better than the current best SZ observation made by the CARMA/SZA array (Culverhouse et al. 2010), with roughly 3 times enhancement in both sensitivity and resolution.

To calibrate the ACA measurement and correct for a potentially small amount of flux loss (Fig. 4 left), we shall use our proprietary APEX-SZ bolometric imaging data at 150 GHz, which were obtained for this cluster in 2009. The APEX-SZ instrument was capable of imaging the extended emission out to 20 arcminutes, although the resolution is poor (1 arcminute). This beam dilution combined with poor weather conditions resulted in a roughly 3.5-sigma detection for this cluster (Fig.2 right). However, the lack of uv-overlap between the APEX-SZ and ALMA 12m array data implies that a combination between these two is not sufficient to reconstruct the full temperature profile. Feathering-in the APEX-SZ data in addition to the proposed ACA measurement can improve the sensitivity of the latter by almost 40%, and provide constraints on any potential large-scale SZ signal that is beyond the maximum recoverable scale of the ACA. A method for combining bolometric and interferometric images have been successfully developed by the team members (Burkutean, Bertoldi et al., in preparation). 

The total time request including observational overheads is roughly 4 hours for the 12m array, and 7.5 hours for the 7m compact array. The cluster XMMU J2235.3-2257 is visible from ALMA for the duration of the Cycle 2 observation.

</prj:justificationText>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
